USENIX The USENIX Association is the original (soon to  celebrate
its  20th anniversary!) nonprofit professional membership organi-
zation of individuals and institutions with an interest in  UNIX.
USENIX extends its support to the broad computing environment in-
cluding advanced tools and technologies such as C++,  X  windows,
interconnectivity  and interoperability, and to professional sub-
specialities such as software development and system  administra-
tion.  The USENIX Association is dedicated to:
* sharing ideas and experience relevant to UNIX and UNIX-like
  computing technologies,
* fostering innovation and communicating both research and techno-
  logical developments,
* providing a neutral forum for the exercise
  of critical thought and airing of technical issues.

USENIX serves its members and supports professional and technical
development  through  a  variety of on-going activities.  Some of
these activities are:
- Sponsoring  Winter  and  Summer  technical conferences  each  year; 
- Sponsoring  and co-sponsoring frequent single-topic conferences,
  symposia and workshops;
- Sponsoring  a highly  regarded tutorial program covering a wide range
  of topics from  introductory  to   advanced;  
- Publishing ;login:, the Association's bi-monthly newsletter featuring
  technical articles, a worldwide calendar of events, USENIX Association
  and System Administrators  Guild News, media reviews, and much more;
- Publishing, with The MIT Press, the refereed technical quarterly
  Computing  Systems; 
- Publishing  proceedings of USENIX conferences and
  symposia and other technical documentation;  -Publishing  a  book
  series in advanced computing systems, in cooperation with The MIT
  Press.  The first book in the new series is The Evolution of C++:
  Language  Design in the Marketplace of Ideas, edited by Jim Waldo
  of Sun Microsystems Laboratories;
- Participating in various ANSI,
  IEEE  and  ISO  standards  efforts.  Reports from the USENIX paid
  representative and others of standards initiatives  and  meetings
  appear regularly in ;login:
- Sponsoring local and special technical groups relevant to the UNIX
  environment.  The  chartering  of the  System  Administrators  Guild
  (SAGE) as a Special Technical Group within USENIX is the most recent.

SAGE, THE SYSTEM ADMINISTRATORS GUILD SAGE, the  System  Adminis-
trators  Guild,  answers the widely felt need for an organization
dedicated to the advancement of system administration as  a  pro-
fession.   SAGE brings together system and network administrators
for professional and technical development, for sharing of  prob-
lems and solutions, and for communicating with users, management,
and vendors on system administration topics.

SAGE is at an exciting point -- it's just over one year  old  and
response  has  been tremendous.  Professional system managers are
greeting SAGE with enthusiasm, as evidenced by the quickly  grow-
ing  membership, rapid recognition from sister organizations, and
growing public recognition of SAGE as both a clearinghouse and  a
representative  on system administration issues.  Currently, SAGE
is moving forward to realize its goals  by: 

- Co-sponsoring  with USENIX  the  annual System Administration (LISA).
  Conferences
- Co-sponsoring with USENIX and FedUNIX  the  Conference  on  Tools  &
  Techniques  for  System  Administration,  Networking  & Security.
  SANS-III will be held April 5-9, 1994  in  Washington,  DC; 
- Co-developing  with  USENIX,  of  a tutorials/invited talks track on
  managing distributed systems and networks at the UniForum Confer-
  ence,  March  21-22,  1994 in San Francisco;
- Creating an archive site -- ftp.sage.usenix.org -- for papers  from
  the  System  Administration  Conferences  and  sys admin-related
  documentation.
- Encouraging formation of local SAGE  groups; 
- Developing  relationships with international affiliates.  SAGE
  affiliates in Australia and in the United Kingdom have recently 
  formed  and  held their  first  conferences; 
- Establishing working groups in areas
  important to system administrators such as jobs, policies, educa-
  tion,  vendors,  and  standards; 
% Two  important current working group projects are:
  - The Jobs group will soon offer its model job descriptions  for 
    system  administrators  at various levels in a pamphlet, free to
    members, and via anonymous ftp;
  - Publication of a series of very practical pamphlets and resource
    guides covering sys admin-related issues and techniques.

