INVITED TALK:
Commercializing Garbage Collection
John R. Ellis, Xerox Palo Alto Research Center <ellis@parc.xerox.com>

Memory management by applications and libraries is getting harder
and  harder,  exacerbated  by  the demands of interface-based and
object-oriented  design.   Automatic  memory  management--garbage
collection--has long been touted by researchers as the best thing
since sliced bread.  Of all the ways researchers have studied for
improving  programmer  productivity,  getting  garbage collection
into the hands of working programmers  could  yield  the  biggest
bang for a small buck.

Now, the time is ripe to add garbage collection to  standard  C++
and make it widely available.  In the last few years, researchers
have developed collection algorithms that require minimal changes
to the language or its implementations.  But the algorithms alone
are insufficient--there must also be a standard, portable defini-
tion  of the language semantics of garbage collection.  Without a
standard, vendors are reluctant to  provide  garbage  collection,
and  programmers  are  reluctant  to  use  non-portable  language
features.

In this talk, I'll discuss the advantages  and  disadvantages  of
garbage  collection in general.  I'll lay out the language-design
issues that must be addressed by any proposal for adding  collec-
tion to C++.  Then I'll try to persuade you garbage collection is
ready for prime time.  And I'll  briefly  describe  one  specific
proposal.

