INVITED TALK:
Video Compression--What Do You Do When Everything is Changing?
  Lawrence  A.  Rowe,  Computer  Science Division-EECS,
  University of California, Berkeley, <larry@postgres.berkeley.edu>

Desktop digital video is a hot topic in  the  research  community
and a rapidly growing commercial market.

Researchers and practitioners working on  applications  that  use
digital  video  (such as video e-mail and conferencing, video-on-
demand servers, and hypermedia courseware) have a  seemingly  un-
limited number of choices of compression algorithms amongst which
to choose including:  CELL-B, DVI, fractals,  H.261/Px64,  motion
JPEG, MPEG1, MPEG2, vector quantization, and wavelet.

Many software implementations of video compression and decompres-
sion have been developed.  The current generation of workstations
can decode and play small-sized videos (e.g., 140x120)  in  real-
time  and medium-size videos (e.g., 320x240) in approximately 2/3
real-time.  At the same time, new  hardware  is  being  announced
every day.

This talk will  survey  the  state-of-the-art  in  digital  video
compression.   I  will  present  a  summary  of  the  major video
compression  algorithms  and  survey   available   hardware   and
software.   The  goal  is to describe today's choices and predict
tomorrow's possibilities.

